\---------- Tim Reitz 10/31/2025: Notes from email that I sent to Jonathan today: 

We're working on figuring out details on who will have access to Silverloom (whether or not the end users, like parents and drivers, will be logging into Silverloom or just accessing some details through a portal like you're building for XFB), so that could impact your design work some. But you could go ahead and get started on the big picture and some details for Devices, Vehicles, Users, and Drivers. 

  


Beyond that, we're not currently sure how / how much data to actually pull in from Traccar vs. just display it somehow (WSGI?). There are various angles that we're coming from here: 

  * With some initial testing, it looks like Traccar is logging data every second as you drive down the road, so an 8-hour road trip averaging 60 mph would result in 28K+ records being created... We don't want that on our hands!
  * Ellis also was not keen on real-time data (location, etc.), or even high-frequency syncing, for server load, etc.
  * And, if we can keep the actual tracking data out of Silverloom entirely, it would reduce Silverloom/CodeCrafters liability in the whole big picture of things. 



We're thinking that Silverloom would be the administrative back-end, managing accounts, subscriptions, users, devices, and vehicles, and sending related notifications. Traccar would be the interactive front-end for end users + source of truth for events/statistics-related reporting, etc., and maybe also the events/statistics-related notifications as well (unless there would be a separate WSGI to do that).
